Ƌ terminalia
. Epandrium separated from tergite 5 by syntergosternite 8, which has 2 spiracles; tergite 6 absent. Sternite 6 absent. Surstylus absent, i.e. fused to epandrium without trace (
Fig. 102
). Cercal plate (
Fig. 103
) moderately divided. Epandrium with numerous incurved setae, curled towards tips and enclosing the anus. Hypandrium attached at lower anterior corner of inner side of epandrium via an apparent praegonite, with 1–2 setae at posterior end; posterior attachment of hypandrial+phallic complex made by an extension from base of phallus to wall of epandrium close to inner dorsal tip of cercal plate. Phallic complex (
Fig. 104
): an apparent praegonite present, appearing at first sight to be a surstylus (
Figs 102, 104
) but firmly fused along its base to hypandrium and only loosely attached to epandrium from which it easily detaches during dissection; postgonite hook-like; phallapodeme enlarged, extending anteriorly over hypandrium and fused to it at mid-length by a plate; phallus simple, fully sclerotised, with no apparent juxta or spinulation, with a rod-like projection at mid-length anteriorly, with a posterior extension that attaches to cercal plate.
